Date: Fri 30 Nov 2001
From: Carol Shoshkes Reiss <Carol.Reiss@nyu.edu>

Possible application of interferon-gamma in treatment
-----------------------------------------------------
With respect to inhibition of smallpox infection, like many other DNA and
RNA viruses studied, the poxvirus _Vaccinia virus_, at least (and all
herpesviruses) are sensitive to nitric oxide (1-5). [There are presumably
no data available relating directly to _Variola virus_ (smallpox virus). -
Mod.CP
Nitric oxide (NO) is produced by NO synthase which has different isoforms
in different tissues. All of these isoforms are induced by inflammatory
cytokines such as Interleukin-12, interferon-gamma and tumor necrosis
factor-alpha (1,6). While excessive activation of NO release might lead to
hypotension, this could be monitored and treated. Therefore consideration
should be given to administration of IFN-gamma to smallpox patients.
References:
1. Reiss CS and Komatsu. Mini review: Does nitric oxide play a critical
role in viral infections? J Virol 1998; 72: 4547-51.
2. Kurapiah G, et al. Inhibition of viral replication by
interferon-gamma-induced nitric oxide synthase. Science 1993; 261: 1445-8.
3. Melkova Z, Esteban M. Inhibition of vaccinia virus DNA replication by
inducible expression of nitric oxide synthase. J Immunol 1995; 155: 5711-8.
4. Rolph MS, et al. Nitric oxide production is increased during murine
vaccinia virus infection, but may not be essential for virus clearance.
Virol 1996; 217: 470-7.
5. Akaike T, Maeda H. Nitric oxide and virus infection. Immunology 2000;
101: 300-8.
6. Komatsu T, et al. Interferon-gamma-induced type 1 nitric oxide synthase
activity inhibits viral replication in neurons. J NeuroImmunol 1996; 68: 101-8.
--
Carol Shoshkes Reiss, PhD
