Date: Fri 30 Nov 2001
From: dan and micky michaeli <michaeli@netvision.net.il>

Fever in smallpox
-----------------
William Baine raises the question of fever and the outcome of smallpox. It
could be helpful to read what Christie had to say (AB Christie (editor).
Infectious diseases: epidemiology and clinical practice. Edinburgh &
London: Livingstone, 1969). On page 198 he refers to the onset of the
disease: "The temperature reaches its height by the second day; 103 F (39.4
C) is commonly found, but it may rise to 104 or 105 F (40 or 40.5 C) even
in cases that are not to prove unduly severe." On p. 201: " The amount of
fever and the severity of the symptoms are proportional to the profuseness
of the rash... " In the gravely ill patient, the fever continues, the rash,
instead of forming dry scabs, becomes slimy and forms foul sloughs, the
patient's condition becomes more and more wretched till death occurs...".
Christie's classic textbook was written by himself alone, based on his
extremely vast experience as a clinician and a public health officer of
many years experience. He wrote only on diseases with which he had solid
personal experience and observations. He held a special appointment, among
many others, of consultant on smallpox, Ministry of Health in England when
smallpox was still very common in many countries.
--
Dan Michaeli MD
Chairman of the Board
Clalit Health Services
Tel Aviv , Israel
<michaeli@netvision.net.il>
<michaeli@clalit.org.il>
